/a></td></tr><tr><th scope="row" class="infobox-label" style="padding-right: 0.5em;">Industry</th><td class="infobox-data category" style="line-height: 1.35em;"><a href="/wiki/Cryptocurrency" title="Cryptocurrency">Cryptocurrency</a></td></tr><tr><th scope="row" class="infobox-label" style="padding-right: 0.5em;">Founded</th><td class="infobox-data" style="line-height: 1.35em;">July 2017<span class="noprint">&#59;&#32;6 years ago</span><span style="display:none">&#160;(<span class="bday dtstart published updated">July 2017</span>)</span><sup id="cite_ref-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-1">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-2">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup></td></tr><tr><th scope="row" class="infobox-label" style="padding-right: 0.5em;">Founders</th><td class="infobox-data agent" style="line-height: 1.35em;"><style data-mw-deduplicate="TemplateStyles:r1126788409">.mw-parser-output .plainlist ol,.mw-parser-output .plainlist ul{line-height:inherit;list-style:none;margin:0;padding:0}.mw-parser-output .plainlist ol li,.mw-parser-output .plainlist ul li{margin-bottom:0}</style><div class="plainlist"><ul><li><a href="/wiki/Changpeng_Zhao" title="Changpeng Zhao">Changpeng Zhao</a></li><li>Yi He<sup id="cite_ref-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-3">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-Bloomberg_-_Crypto&#39;s_Most_Powerful_Woman_Speaks_Out_as_Crisis_Rocks_Binance_4-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Bloomberg_-_Crypto&#39;s_Most_Powerful_Woman_Speaks_Out_as_Crisis_Rocks_Binance-4">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup></li></ul></div></td></tr><tr><th scope="row" class="infobox-label" style="padding-right: 0.5em;">Headquarters</th><td class="infobox-data adr" style="line-height: 1.35em;"><div style="display: inline;" class="country-name">Unknown</div></td></tr><tr><th scope="row" class="infobox-label" style="padding-right: 0.5em;"><div style="display: inline-block; line-height: 1.2em; padding: .1em 0;">Area served</div></th><td class="infobox-data" style="line-height: 1.35em;">Global, except for the <a href="/wiki/United_States" title="United States">United States</a><sup id="cite_ref-Forbes_2020-10-28_5-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Forbes_2020-10-28-5">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup></td></tr><tr><th scope="row" class="infobox-label" style="padding-right: 0.5em;"><div style="display: inline-block; line-height: 1.2em; padding: .1em 0;">Key people</div></th><td class="infobox-data agent" style="line-height: 1.35em;"><a href="/wiki/Richard_Teng" title="Richard Teng">Richard Teng</a> (<a href="/wiki/CEO" class="mw-redirect" title="CEO">CEO</a>)<sup id="cite_ref-6" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-6">&#91;6&#93;</a></sup></td></tr><tr><th scope="row" class="infobox-label" style="padding-right: 0.5em;">Products</th><td class="infobox-data" style="line-height: 1.35em;"><a href="/wiki/Cryptocurrency_exchange" title="Cryptocurrency exchange">Cryptocurrency exchange</a>, <a href="/wiki/Cryptocurrencies" class="mw-redirect" title="Cryptocurrencies">cryptocurrencies</a></td></tr><tr><th scope="row" class="infobox-label" style="padding-right: 0.5em;">Revenue</th><td class="infobox-data" style="line-height: 1.35em;"><a href="/wiki/US$" class="mw-redirect" title="US$">US$</a>12 billion (2022)<sup id="cite_ref-7" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-7">&#91;7&#93;</a></sup></td></tr><tr><th scope="row" class="infobox-label" style="padding-right: 0.5em;"><div style="display: inline-block; line-height: 1.2em; padding: .1em 0;">Number of employees</div></th><td class="infobox-data" style="line-height: 1.35em;">7,000 (2023)<sup id="cite_ref-8" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-8">&#91;8&#93;</a></sup></td></tr><tr><th scope="row" class="infobox-label" style="padding-right: 0.5em;"><a href="/wiki/Subsidiary" title="Subsidiary">Subsidiaries</a></th><td class="infobox-data" style="line-height: 1.35em;"><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1126788409"><div class="plainlist"><ul><li>Sakura Exchange</li><li>Trust Wallet</li><li>{{ env('APP_NAME') }} Charity</li></ul></div></td></tr><tr><th scope="row" class="infobox-label" style="padding-right: 0.5em;">Website</th><td class="infobox-data" style="line-height: 1.35em;"><span class="url"><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.binance.com/">www<wbr />.binance<wbr />.com</a></span> <span class="mw-valign-text-top noprint" typeof="mw:File/Frameless"><a href="https://www.wikidata.org/wiki/Q51403327#P856" title="Edit this at Wikidata"><img alt="Edit this at Wikidata" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/8/8a/OOjs_UI_icon_edit-ltr-progressive.svg/10px-OOjs_UI_icon_edit-ltr-progressive.svg.png" decoding="async" width="10" height="10" class="mw-file-element" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/8/8a/OOjs_UI_icon_edit-ltr-progressive.svg/15px-OOjs_UI_icon_edit-ltr-progressive.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/8/8a/OOjs_UI_icon_edit-ltr-progressive.svg/20px-OOjs_UI_icon_edit-ltr-progressive.svg.png 2x" data-file-width="20" data-file-height="20" /></a></span></td></tr></tbody></table>
<p><b>{{ env('APP_NAME') }} Holdings Ltd.</b>, branded <b>{{ env('APP_NAME')}}</b>, is a global<sup id="cite_ref-9" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-9">&#91;9&#93;</a></sup> company that operates the largest <a href="/wiki/Cryptocurrency_exchange" title="Cryptocurrency exchange">cryptocurrency exchange</a> in terms of daily trading <a href="/wiki/Volume_(finance)" title="Volume (finance)">volume</a> of <a href="/wiki/Cryptocurrencies" class="mw-redirect" title="Cryptocurrencies">cryptocurrencies</a>. {{ env('APP_NAME') }} was founded in 2017 by <a href="/wiki/Changpeng_Zhao" title="Changpeng Zhao">Changpeng Zhao</a>, a developer who had previously created <a href="/wiki/High_frequency_trading" class="mw-redirect" title="High frequency trading">high-frequency trading</a> software. {{ env('APP_NAME') }} was initially based in China, then moved to Japan shortly before the Chinese government restricted cryptocurrency companies. {{ env('APP_NAME') }} subsequently left Japan for Malta and currently has no official company headquarters.
</p><p>{{ env('APP_NAME') }} has been the subject of lawsuits and challenges from regulatory authorities throughout its history. As a result, {{ env('APP_NAME') }} has been banned from operating or ordered to cease operations in some countries, and has been issued fines. It has been alleged that {{ env('APP_NAME') }} could be used as a funding mechanism for terrorist groups. In November 2023, the company pleaded guilty in a U.S. federal court to money laundering, unlicensed money transmitting, and sanctions violations. In 2021, {{ env('APP_NAME') }} was put under investigation by both the <a href="/wiki/United_States_Department_of_Justice" title="United States Department of Justice">United States Department of Justice</a> and <a href="/wiki/Internal_Revenue_Service" title="Internal Revenue Service">Internal Revenue Service</a> on allegations of <a href="/wiki/Money_laundering" title="Money laundering">money laundering</a> and tax offenses.<sup id="cite_ref-Daily_Newsbrief_10-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Daily_Newsbrief-10">&#91;10&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-bloomberg.com_11-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-bloomberg.com-11">&#91;11&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-reuters.com_12-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-reuters.com-12">&#91;12&#93;</a></sup> The UK's <a href="/wiki/Financial_Conduct_Authority" title="Financial Conduct Authority">Financial Conduct Authority</a> ordered {{ env('APP_NAME') }} to stop all regulated activity in the United Kingdom in June 2021.<sup id="cite_ref-13" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-13">&#91;13&#93;</a></sup> That same year, {{ env('APP_NAME') }} shared client data, including names and addresses, with the Russian government.<sup id="cite_ref-14" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-14">&#91;14&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<meta property="mw:PageProp/toc" />
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="History">History</span></h2>
<figure class="mw-default-size" typeof="mw:File/Thumb"><a href="/wiki/File:5_years_birthday_Binance_cake_in_Paris_-_2022-07-08.jpg" class="mw-file-description"><img src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e5/5_years_birthday_Binance_cake_in_Paris_-_2022-07-08.jpg/220px-5_years_birthday_Binance_cake_in_Paris_-_2022-07-08.jpg" decoding="async" width="220" height="293" class="mw-file-element" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e5/5_years_birthday_Binance_cake_in_Paris_-_2022-07-08.jpg/330px-5_years_birthday_Binance_cake_in_Paris_-_2022-07-08.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e5/5_years_birthday_Binance_cake_in_Paris_-_2022-07-08.jpg/440px-5_years_birthday_Binance_cake_in_Paris_-_2022-07-08.jpg 2x" data-file-width="3024" data-file-height="4032" /></a><figcaption>5 years birthday {{ env('APP_NAME') }} cake in Paris in July 2022.</figcaption></figure>
<h3><span id="2013.E2.80.932017:_company_beginnings_and_move_out_of_China"></span><span class="mw-headline" id="2013–2017:_company_beginnings_and_move_out_of_China">2013–2017: company beginnings and move out of China</span></h3>
<p>CEO Changpeng Zhao founded Fusion Systems in 2005 in <a href="/wiki/Shanghai" title="Shanghai">Shanghai</a>; the company built <a href="/wiki/High-frequency_trading" title="High-frequency trading">high-frequency trading</a> systems for <a href="/wiki/Stockbrokers" class="mw-redirect" title="Stockbrokers">stockbrokers</a>. In 2013, he joined <a href="/wiki/Blockchain.info" class="mw-redirect" title="Blockchain.info">Blockchain.info</a> as the third member of the <a href="/wiki/Cryptocurrency_wallet" title="Cryptocurrency wallet">cryptocurrency wallet</a>'s team. He also worked at OKCoin as CTO for less than a year, a platform for <a href="/wiki/Spot_contract" title="Spot contract">spot</a> trading between <a href="/wiki/Fiat_money" title="Fiat money">fiat</a> and <a href="/wiki/Digital_asset" title="Digital asset">digital assets</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-Forbes2018_15-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Forbes2018-15">&#91;15&#93;</a></sup> He was hired at this position in 2014 by Yi He, with whom he co-founded {{ env('APP_NAME') }} several years later.<sup id="cite_ref-Bloomberg_-_Crypto&#39;s_Most_Powerful_Woman_Speaks_Out_as_Crisis_Rocks_Binance_4-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Bloomberg_-_Crypto&#39;s_Most_Powerful_Woman_Speaks_Out_as_Crisis_Rocks_Binance-4">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>The company was founded in 2017 in <a href="/wiki/China" title="China">China</a> but moved its servers and headquarters out of the country in advance of the Chinese government's ban on cryptocurrency trading in September 2017.<sup id="cite_ref-16" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-16">&#91;16&#93;</a></sup> Zhao asked He to join {{ env('APP_NAME') }}, and she helped rewrite parts of the white paper for {{ env('APP_NAME') }}'s $15 million initial coin offering.<sup id="cite_ref-Bloomberg_-_Crypto&#39;s_Most_Powerful_Woman_Speaks_Out_as_Crisis_Rocks_Binance_4-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Bloomberg_-_Crypto&#39;s_Most_Powerful_Woman_Speaks_Out_as_Crisis_Rocks_Binance-4">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h3><span id="2018.E2.80.932019:_launch_of_stablecoin_and_security_breach"></span><span class="mw-headline" id="2018–2019:_launch_of_stablecoin_and_security_breach">2018–2019: launch of stablecoin and security breach</span></h3>
<p>In January 2018 it was the largest <a href="/wiki/Cryptocurrency_exchange" title="Cryptocurrency exchange">cryptocurrency exchange</a> with a market capitalization of $1.3 billion,<sup id="cite_ref-Bloomberg201801_17-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Bloomberg201801-17">&#91;17&#93;</a></sup> a title it had retained as late as April 2021, despite competition from <a href="/wiki/Coinbase" title="Coinbase">Coinbase</a>, among others.<sup id="cite_ref-18" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-18">&#91;18&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>In March 2018, {{ env('APP_NAME') }} announced its intentions to open an office in <a href="/wiki/Malta" title="Malta">Malta</a> after stricter regulations in Japan and China.<sup id="cite_ref-Bloomberg201803_19-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Bloomberg201803-19">&#91;19&#93;</a></sup> In April 2018, {{ env('APP_NAME') }} signed a <a href="/wiki/Memorandum_of_understanding" title="Memorandum of understanding">memorandum of understanding</a> with the government of <a href="/wiki/Bermuda" title="Bermuda">Bermuda</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-Ber_News_2019-01-19_20-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Ber_News_2019-01-19-20">&#91;20&#93;</a></sup> Months later, a similar memorandum was signed with the Malta Stock Exchange to develop a platform for trading security tokens.<sup id="cite_ref-21" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-21">&#91;21&#93;</a></sup> In 2019, the company announced {{ env('APP_NAME') }} Jersey, an independent entity from its parent {{ env('APP_NAME') }}.com exchange, with the aim to expand its European influence. <a href="/wiki/Jersey" title="Jersey">Jersey</a>-based exchange offers fiat-to-cryptocurrency pairs, including the <a href="/wiki/Euro" title="Euro">Euro</a> and the <a href="/wiki/British_pound" class="mw-redirect" title="British pound">British pound</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-22" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-22">&#91;22&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>In April 2018, {{ env('APP_NAME') }} launched the {{ env('APP_NAME') }} Charity Foundation. The charity's goal is to support the advancement of blockchain-enabled philanthropy with a focus on third-world countries.<sup id="cite_ref-23" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-23">&#91;23&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>In June 2018, {{ env('APP_NAME') }} and three other firms raised $65 million for sports blockchain company <a href="/wiki/Chiliz" title="Chiliz">Chiliz</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-24" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-24">&#91;24&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>In July 2018, {{ env('APP_NAME') }} acquired Trust Wallet, a decentralized cryptocurrency wallet for an undisclosed sum. However, {{ env('APP_NAME') }}, confirmed that the compensation is a mixture of cash, {{ env('APP_NAME') }} stock, and a portion of its BNB token.<sup id="cite_ref-25" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-25">&#91;25&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>In August 2018, {{ env('APP_NAME') }} along with three other big exchanges raised $32 million for a "<a href="/wiki/Stablecoin" title="Stablecoin">stablecoin</a>" project. The idea of stablecoins is to provide a cryptocurrency without the notorious volatility of <a href="/wiki/Bitcoin" title="Bitcoin">Bitcoin</a> and other popular <a href="/wiki/Digital_asset" title="Digital asset">digital assets</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-26" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-26">&#91;26&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>In January 2019, {{ env('APP_NAME') }} announced that it had partnered with Israel-based payment processor Simplex to enable cryptocurrency purchases with debit and credit cards, including <a href="/wiki/Visa_Inc." title="Visa Inc.">Visa</a> and <a href="/wiki/Mastercard" title="Mastercard">Mastercard</a>. The purchases are subject to Simplex's local bank policies and are limited to Bitcoin, <a href="/wiki/Ethereum" title="Ethereum">Ethereum</a>, <a href="/wiki/Litecoin" title="Litecoin">Litecoin</a> and <a href="/wiki/Ripple_(payment_protocol)" title="Ripple (payment protocol)">Ripple's</a> <a href="/wiki/XRP" class="mw-redirect" title="XRP">XRP</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-27" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-27">&#91;27&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>On 7 May 2019, {{ env('APP_NAME') }} revealed that it had been the victim of a "large scale security breach" in which hackers had stolen 7,000 Bitcoin worth around $40 million at the time.<sup id="cite_ref-28" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-28">&#91;28&#93;</a></sup> {{ env('APP_NAME') }} CEO Changpeng Zhao said the hackers "used a variety of techniques, including <a href="/wiki/Phishing" title="Phishing">phishing</a>, viruses and other attacks" and structured their transaction "in a way that passed our existing security checks."<sup id="cite_ref-29" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-29">&#91;29&#93;</a></sup> {{ env('APP_NAME') }} halted further withdrawals and deposits but allowed trading to continue. The site pledged to reimburse customers through its "Secure Asset Fund for Users (SAFU)".<sup id="cite_ref-30" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-30">&#91;30&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-31" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-31">&#91;31&#93;</a></sup> Withdrawals resumed by 19 May.<sup id="cite_ref-32" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-32">&#91;32&#93;</a></sup><sup class="noprint Inline-Template noprint noexcerpt Template-Fact" style="white-space:nowrap;">&#91;<i><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:NOTRS" class="mw-redirect" title="Wikipedia:NOTRS"><span title="Citation is the {{ env('APP_NAME') }} company website, which is not objective. (August 2022)">better&#160;source&#160;needed</span></a></i>&#93;</sup>
</p><p>In June 2019 the company announced it would prohibit US passport holders as well as anyone residing in the US, and would set up a new entity {{ env('APP_NAME') }}.us to support those customers.<sup id="cite_ref-33" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-33">&#91;33&#93;</a></sup> Later in 2023 Forbes leaked a document allegedly from {{ env('APP_NAME') }} titled "TaiChi" that proposed this regulatory solution to reduce US regulatory risk.<sup id="cite_ref-34" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-34">&#91;34&#93;</a></sup> {{ env('APP_NAME') }} subsequently denied the document, sued Forbes for defamation, and subsequently dropped the lawsuit.<sup id="cite_ref-35" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-35">&#91;35&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>In September 2019, the exchange began offering <a href="/wiki/Perpetual_futures" title="Perpetual futures">perpetual futures</a> contracts, allowing leverage as high as 125 times the value of the contracts.<sup id="cite_ref-36" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-36">&#91;36&#93;</a></sup> In November 2019, {{ env('APP_NAME') }} announced it was acquiring <a href="/wiki/India" title="India">Indian</a> bitcoin exchange WazirX, which became disputed in August 2022 when {{ env('APP_NAME') }} founder Zhao claimed the deal was never signed.<sup id="cite_ref-37" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-37">&#91;37&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h3><span id="2020.E2.80.932023:_acquisitions_and_investments"></span><span class="mw-headline" id="2020–2023:_acquisitions_and_investments">2020–2023: acquisitions and investments</span></h3>
<p>On 21 February 2020, the <a href="/wiki/Malta_Financial_Services_Authority" title="Malta Financial Services Authority">Malta Financial Services Authority</a> (MFSA) issued a public statement responding to media reports referring to {{ env('APP_NAME') }} as a '<a href="/wiki/Malta" title="Malta">Malta</a>-based' cryptocurrency company. The statement noted that {{ env('APP_NAME') }} "is not authorized by the MFSA to operate in the cryptocurrency sphere and is therefore not subject to regulatory oversight by the MFSA." The MFSA added that it was "assessing if {{ env('APP_NAME') }} has any activities in Malta which may not fall within the realm of regulatory oversight."<sup id="cite_ref-38" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-38">&#91;38&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>In July 2020, {{ env('APP_NAME') }} announced a "strategic partnership" with a Chinese <a href="/wiki/State-owned_enterprise" title="State-owned enterprise">state-owned enterprise</a> under the <a href="/wiki/State-owned_Assets_Supervision_and_Administration_Commission_of_the_State_Council" title="State-owned Assets Supervision and Administration Commission of the State Council">State-owned Assets Supervision and Administration Commission of the State Council</a> and that {{ env('APP_NAME') }} had joined a group "aiming to facilitate" the <a href="/wiki/Belt_and_Road_Initiative" title="Belt and Road Initiative">Belt and Road Initiative</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-39" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-39">&#91;39&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-40" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-40">&#91;40&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>On 28 October 2020, <i><a href="/wiki/Forbes_magazine" class="mw-redirect" title="Forbes magazine">Forbes</a></i> staff released leaked documents showing that {{ env('APP_NAME') }} and Changpeng Zhao created an elaborate corporate structure designed to intentionally deceive United States regulators and secretly profit from cryptocurrency investors located in the country.<sup id="cite_ref-Forbes_2020-10-28_5-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Forbes_2020-10-28-5">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup> {{ env('APP_NAME') }} officially blocks access from <a href="/wiki/IP_addresses" class="mw-redirect" title="IP addresses">IP addresses</a> located in the United States, but "potential customers would be taught how to evade geographic restrictions", <i>Forbes</i> claimed.<sup id="cite_ref-Forbes_2020-10-28_5-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Forbes_2020-10-28-5">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>In May 2021 it was reported that {{ env('APP_NAME') }} was under investigation by both the <a href="/wiki/Internal_Revenue_Service" title="Internal Revenue Service">Internal Revenue Service</a> and the <a href="/wiki/United_States_Department_of_Justice" title="United States Department of Justice">United States Department of Justice</a> on allegations of money laundering and tax offenses.<sup id="cite_ref-Daily_Newsbrief_10-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Daily_Newsbrief-10">&#91;10&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-bloomberg.com_11-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-bloomberg.com-11">&#91;11&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-reuters.com_12-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-reuters.com-12">&#91;12&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>In February 2022, {{ env('APP_NAME') }} took a $200 million stake in <i>Forbes</i>.<sup id="cite_ref-41" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-41">&#91;41&#93;</a></sup> It's unclear if this investment was ever completed. In May 2022, Forbes Global Media Holdings halted plans to go public via a merger with Magnum Opus Acquisition Ltd, a Hong Kong-based <a href="/wiki/Special-purpose_acquisition_company" title="Special-purpose acquisition company">special-purpose acquisition company</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-42" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-42">&#91;42&#93;</a></sup> Zhao said the plan had "changed a little bit, but I believe that's still in discussions."<sup id="cite_ref-43" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-43">&#91;43&#93;</a></sup> In February 2023, Zhao tweeted his disappointment that Forbes "continues to write baseless articles" about {{ env('APP_NAME') }}.<sup id="cite_ref-44" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-44">&#91;44&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>In March 2022, amidst the <a href="/wiki/2022_Russian_invasion_of_Ukraine" class="mw-redirect" title="2022 Russian invasion of Ukraine">2022 Russian invasion of Ukraine</a>, {{ env('APP_NAME') }}'s CEO Changpeng Zhao, refused to ban users from Russia, citing "financial freedom".<sup id="cite_ref-45" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-45">&#91;45&#93;</a></sup> {{ env('APP_NAME') }} later softened the tone of their opposition but not their policy, and also pointed to their donation of $10 million for humanitarian needs in Ukraine.<sup id="cite_ref-46" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-46">&#91;46&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>Over 2022, <i><a href="/wiki/Reuters" title="Reuters">Reuters</a></i> released several investigative reports on {{ env('APP_NAME') }}. In January, Reuters documented multiple instances where {{ env('APP_NAME') }} had withheld information from government investigators and business partners and had ignored warnings from their own compliance teams regarding money laundering risks and poor <a href="/wiki/Know_your_customer" title="Know your customer">know your customer</a> compliance. {{ env('APP_NAME') }} disputed the accuracy of this report.<sup id="cite_ref-47" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-47">&#91;47&#93;</a></sup> In June, Reuters found that {{ env('APP_NAME') }} had acted as a conduit for the laundering of at least $2.35 billion from hacks, $780 million dollars laundered from the Russian <a href="/wiki/Darknet" title="Darknet">darknet</a> market <a href="/wiki/Hydra_Market" title="Hydra Market">Hydra</a>, and €800 million from investment scams. The report also found that {{ env('APP_NAME') }} had been used by the <a href="/wiki/Lazarus_Group" title="Lazarus Group">Lazarus Group</a> to launder funds stolen by <a href="/wiki/North_Korea" title="North Korea">North Korea</a> to support its weapons program. {{ env('APP_NAME') }} dispute these findings.<sup id="cite_ref-48" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-48">&#91;48&#93;</a></sup> In April, <i>Reuters</i> reported that, in 2021, {{ env('APP_NAME') }} shared information with <a href="/wiki/Rosfinmonitoring" title="Rosfinmonitoring">Rosfinmonitoring</a> about funds raised by late Russian opposition leader <a href="/wiki/Alexei_Navalny" title="Alexei Navalny">Alexei Navalny</a>'s network.<sup id="cite_ref-49" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-49">&#91;49&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-50" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-50">&#91;50&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>In March 2023, the exchange banned Russian residents from buying euros and dollars through its p2p service. European users, in turn, lost the ability to buy rubles.<sup id="cite_ref-51" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-51">&#91;51&#93;</a></sup> In September 2023, {{ env('APP_NAME') }} announced it was leaving Russia and selling its business to the CommEX platform, which had been launched the previous week.<sup id="cite_ref-52" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-52">&#91;52&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-53" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-53">&#91;53&#93;</a></sup> {{ env('APP_NAME') }} accounts of Russian users were able to transfer to the new platform until March 2024. CommEX shut down on 10 May 2024.<sup id="cite_ref-54" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-54">&#91;54&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>On 27 May 2022, {{ env('APP_NAME') }} announced the registration of its legal entity in Italy and plans to open offices in the country. At the time, the company was also seeking registration in more European countries, such as Switzerland, Sweden, Spain, Netherlands, Portugal and Austria.<sup id="cite_ref-55" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-55">&#91;55&#93;</a></sup> {{ env('APP_NAME') }} registered to operate in Spain in July 2022,<sup id="cite_ref-Reuters_July2022_56-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Reuters_July2022-56">&#91;56&#93;</a></sup> and in Sweden in January 2023.<sup id="cite_ref-Reuters_January2023_57-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Reuters_January2023-57">&#91;57&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-58" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-58">&#91;58&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>On 13 June 2022 {{ env('APP_NAME') }} announced that users would, for an unspecified period of time, be unable to withdraw their funds held in Bitcoin, as the value of cryptocurrencies suffered serious declines.<sup id="cite_ref-59" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-59">&#91;59&#93;</a></sup> Two hours after that announcement, Bitcoin withdrawals were allowed to resume.<sup id="cite_ref-60" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-60">&#91;60&#93;</a></sup><sup class="noprint Inline-Template noprint noexcerpt Template-Fact" style="white-space:nowrap;">&#91;<i><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:NOTRS" class="mw-redirect" title="Wikipedia:NOTRS"><span title="Citation is the {{ env('APP_NAME') }} company website, which is not objective. (August 2022)">better&#160;source&#160;needed</span></a></i>&#93;</sup>
</p><p>{{ env('APP_NAME') }} sponsored the <a href="/wiki/Africa_Cup_of_Nations" title="Africa Cup of Nations">Africa Cup of Nations</a> in 2021.<sup id="cite_ref-61" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-61">&#91;61&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-62" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-62">&#91;62&#93;</a></sup> It is also taking crypto education to many countries on the continent.<sup id="cite_ref-63" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-63">&#91;63&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>{{ env('APP_NAME') }} invested US$500 million towards the <a href="/wiki/Acquisition_of_Twitter_by_Elon_Musk" title="Acquisition of Twitter by Elon Musk">acquisition of Twitter by Elon Musk</a> that completed in October 2022. Following the investment, the company announced the creation of a team to work on how blockchain and cryptocurrencies could be helpful to <a href="/wiki/Twitter,_Inc." title="Twitter, Inc.">Twitter</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-64" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-64">&#91;64&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-65" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-65">&#91;65&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>On 8 November 2022, {{ env('APP_NAME') }} offered to buy rival cryptocurrency exchange <a href="/wiki/FTX_(company)" class="mw-redirect" title="FTX (company)">FTX</a>'s non-US operations (FTX.com) to help cover the latter's <a href="/wiki/Bankruptcy_of_FTX" title="Bankruptcy of FTX">liquidity crunch</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-bb20221108_66-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-bb20221108-66">&#91;66&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-67" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-67">&#91;67&#93;</a></sup> {{ env('APP_NAME') }} backed out of the deal the next day citing concerns about FTX's business practices and investigations by US financial regulators.<sup id="cite_ref-68" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-68">&#91;68&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>On 30 November 2022, {{ env('APP_NAME') }} purchased Sakura Exchange. The acquisition allowed {{ env('APP_NAME') }} to re-enter the Japanese cryptocurrency market.<sup id="cite_ref-69" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-69">&#91;69&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-70" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-70">&#91;70&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>In July 2023, several senior executives resigned from the company.<sup id="cite_ref-71" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-71">&#91;71&#93;</a></sup> <i>The Wall Street Journal</i> reported that {{ env('APP_NAME') }} had cut its global workforce by as many as 1,000 staff.<sup id="cite_ref-72" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-72">&#91;72&#93;</a></sup> CNBC reported that the number of staff cuts could total 3,000 by the end of 2023.<sup id="cite_ref-73" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-73">&#91;73&#93;</a></sup> Zhao didn't deny layoffs were occurring but claimed both the reported numbers and the reasons for the senior executive departures weren't accurate. In June 2023 {{ env('APP_NAME') }} had 790 million US dollars in outflows after the SEC announced its lawsuit and Forbes reported that the company had 120 million users globally.<sup id="cite_ref-74" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-74">&#91;74&#93;</a></sup> On November 21, 2023, a US judge convicted {{ env('APP_NAME') }} on multiple charges—including violations of the Bank Secrecy Act, money laundering schemes, unlicensed money transmitting, and sanctions violations. As part of the plea deal, the company agreed to pay $4 billion in fines, and Changpeng Zhao stepped down as CEO with a $50 million fine.<sup id="cite_ref-:1_75-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-:1-75">&#91;75&#93;</a></sup> Zhao was succeeded by <a href="/wiki/Richard_Teng" title="Richard Teng">Richard Teng</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-:1_75-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-:1-75">&#91;75&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>According to a 2024 report in <i>The Wall Street Journal</i>, in 2023 {{ env('APP_NAME') }} fired several members of its internal investigation team who were tasked with investigating <a href="/wiki/Market_manipulation" title="Market manipulation">market manipulation</a> such as <a href="/wiki/Pump_and_dump" title="Pump and dump">pump and dump</a> schemes and <a href="/wiki/Wash_trading" class="mw-redirect" title="Wash trading">wash trading</a>. According to <i>The Wall Street Journal</i>, an internal investigation within {{ env('APP_NAME') }} found that a VIP client of the company, a trading and investment firm named DWF Labs, had previously advertised its ability to manipulate the market by generating "believable" artificial volume to increase the price of tokens. The investigation also found examples of DWF selling tokens its founder had promoted causing a crash in those token's price, which is consistent with a pump and dump scheme, and is against Binanace's terms of service. In response to this report, {{ env('APP_NAME') }} fired the investigators and retained DWF as a client, saying that the self trading could have been accidental and that the internal team collaborated too closely with one of DWF's competitors. {{ env('APP_NAME') }} has denied any wrongdoing.<sup id="cite_ref-76" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-76">&#91;76&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>According to a 2024 study by John Griffin, a finance professor at the <a href="/wiki/University_of_Texas_at_Austin" title="University of Texas at Austin">University of Texas at Austin</a>, {{ env('APP_NAME') }} is the most popular exchange used in <a href="/wiki/Pig_butchering_scam" title="Pig butchering scam">pig butchering scams</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-Faux_77-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Faux-77">&#91;77&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-78" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-78">&#91;78&#93;</a></sup> {{ env('APP_NAME') }} has occasionally cooperated with US law enforcement to return money lost in such scams.<sup id="cite_ref-Faux_77-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Faux-77">&#91;77&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-79" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-79">&#91;79&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-80" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-80">&#91;80&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-81" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-81">&#91;81&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Tokens">Tokens</span></h2>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="BNB">BNB</span></h3>
<link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1228913792"><table class="infobox"><caption class="infobox-title">Build'N'Build</caption><tbody><tr><td colspan="2" class="infobox-image"><span typeof="mw:File"><a href="/wiki/File:BNB,_native_cryptocurrency_for_the_Binance_Smart_Chain.svg" class="mw-file-description"><img src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/1c/BNB%2C_native_cryptocurrency_for_the_Binance_Smart_Chain.svg/150px-BNB%2C_native_cryptocurrency_for_the_Binance_Smart_Chain.svg.png" decoding="async" width="150" height="150" class="mw-file-element" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/1c/BNB%2C_native_cryptocurrency_for_the_Binance_Smart_Chain.svg/225px-BNB%2C_native_cryptocurrency_for_the_Binance_Smart_Chain.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/1c/BNB%2C_native_cryptocurrency_for_the_Binance_Smart_Chain.svg/300px-BNB%2C_native_cryptocurrency_for_the_Binance_Smart_Chain.svg.png 2x" data-file-width="512" data-file-height="512" /></a></span></td></tr><tr><th colspan="2" class="infobox-header" style="background-color: silver">Denominations</th></tr><tr><th scope="row" class="infobox-label">Code</th><td class="infobox-data">BNB</td></tr><tr><th scope="row" class="infobox-label">Previous names</th><td class="infobox-data">{{ env('APP_NAME') }} Coin</td></tr><tr><th colspan="2" class="infobox-header" style="background-color: silver">Development</th></tr><tr><th scope="row" class="infobox-label"><a href="/wiki/White_paper" title="White paper">White paper</a></th><td class="infobox-data"><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://cryptoverze.s3.us-east-2.amazonaws.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/10011630/Binance-Coin-BNB-Whitepaper_reduce.pdf">BNB Whitepaper</a></td></tr><tr><th scope="row" class="infobox-label">Initial release</th><td class="infobox-data">July&#160;2017<span class="noprint">&#59;&#32;6&#160;years ago</span><span style="display:none">&#160;(<span class="bday dtstart published updated">2017-07</span>)</span></td></tr><tr><th scope="row" class="infobox-label">Development status</th><td class="infobox-data">Active</td></tr><tr><th colspan="2" class="infobox-header" style="background-color: silver">Ledger</th></tr><tr><th scope="row" class="infobox-label">Block explorer</th><td class="infobox-data">bscscan.com</td></tr><tr><th scope="row" class="infobox-label">Supply limit</th><td class="infobox-data">200,000,000</td></tr><tr><th colspan="2" class="infobox-header" style="background-color: silver">Valuation</th></tr><tr><th scope="row" class="infobox-label"><a href="/wiki/Exchange_rate" title="Exchange rate">Exchange rate</a></th><td class="infobox-data">~300$</td></tr><tr><th colspan="2" class="infobox-header" style="background-color: silver">Website</th></tr><tr><th scope="row" class="infobox-label">Website</th><td class="infobox-data">www.bnbchain.org</td></tr></tbody></table>
<p>BNB (Build'N'Build) is a token on the BNB chain. It was originally called {{ env('APP_NAME') }} Coin when it was launched in July 2017,<sup class="noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" style="white-space:nowrap;">&#91;<i><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title="Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span title="This claim needs references to reliable sources. (May 2024)">citation needed</span></a></i>&#93;</sup> for users to pay fees on the company's platform. By 2021, BNB had the third highest market capitalization among cryptocurrencies.<sup id="cite_ref-:0_82-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-:0-82">&#91;82&#93;</a></sup> The token was initially on the Ethereum network, then moved to BNB Smart Chain when it was released in September 2020.<sup id="cite_ref-83" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-83">&#91;83&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-84" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-84">&#91;84&#93;</a></sup> In February 2022, the company changed the token's name to Build'N'Build. At that time, {{ env('APP_NAME') }} Smart Chain was also renamed to BNB Chain. BNB Chain had previously been criticized for being overly centralized, which had led to several exploits on the network.<sup id="cite_ref-YF-BSC_85-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-YF-BSC-85">&#91;85&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-86" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-86">&#91;86&#93;</a></sup> BNB had 44 validators As of October 2022<sup class="plainlinks noexcerpt noprint asof-tag update" style="display:none;"><a class="external text" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Binance&amp;action=edit">&#91;update&#93;</a></sup>.<sup id="cite_ref-Reuters_October2022_87-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Reuters_October2022-87">&#91;87&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="BUSD">BUSD</span></h3>
<link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1228913792"><table class="infobox"><caption class="infobox-title">{{ env('APP_NAME') }} USD</caption><tbody><tr><th colspan="2" class="infobox-header" style="background-color: silver">Denominations</th></tr><tr><th scope="row" class="infobox-label">Code</th><td class="infobox-data">BUSD</td></tr><tr><th colspan="2" class="infobox-header" style="background-color: silver">Development</th></tr><tr><th scope="row" class="infobox-label">Initial release</th><td class="infobox-data">September&#160;10, 2019<span class="noprint">&#59;&#32;4 years ago</span><span style="display:none">&#160;(<span class="bday dtstart published updated">2019-09-10</span>)</span></td></tr><tr><th scope="row" class="infobox-label">Development status</th><td class="infobox-data">Active</td></tr><tr><th colspan="2" class="infobox-header" style="background-color: silver">Ledger</th></tr><tr><th scope="row" class="infobox-label">Circulating supply</th><td class="infobox-data">19,016,156,336.57 (As of 23 August 2022)</td></tr><tr><th scope="row" class="infobox-label">Supply limit</th><td class="infobox-data">Unlimited</td></tr><tr><th colspan="2" class="infobox-header" style="background-color: silver">Valuation</th></tr><tr><th scope="row" class="infobox-label"><a href="/wiki/Exchange_rate" title="Exchange rate">Exchange rate</a></th><td class="infobox-data">Pegged to the <a href="/wiki/US_Dollar" class="mw-redirect" title="US Dollar">US Dollar</a></td></tr><tr><th colspan="2" class="infobox-header" style="background-color: silver">Website</th></tr><tr><th scope="row" class="infobox-label">Website</th><td class="infobox-data">binance.com/en/busd</td></tr></tbody></table>
<p>BUSD, or {{ env('APP_NAME') }} USD, is a <a href="/wiki/US_Dollar" class="mw-redirect" title="US Dollar">US Dollar</a> pegged stablecoin issued by {{ env('APP_NAME') }}.<sup id="cite_ref-88" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-88">&#91;88&#93;</a></sup> According to {{ env('APP_NAME') }} it is backed 1:1 by a reserve of US Dollars and was founded by them in partnership with <a href="/wiki/Paxos_Trust_Company" title="Paxos Trust Company">Paxos</a> who is the issuer of the token.<sup class="noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" style="white-space:nowrap;">&#91;<i><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title="Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span title="This claim needs references to reliable sources. (May 2024)">citation needed</span></a></i>&#93;</sup>
</p><p>In January 2023, Bloomberg reported that {{ env('APP_NAME') }}-Peg BUSD "was often undercollateralized between 2020 and 2021. On three separate occasions, the gap between reserves and supply surpassed $1 billion." A {{ env('APP_NAME') }} spokesperson said the "process of maintaining the backing … has not always been flawless" but "has been much improved with enhanced discrepancy checks."<sup id="cite_ref-89" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-89">&#91;89&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>as of 2022<sup class="plainlinks noexcerpt noprint asof-tag update" style="display:none;"><a class="external text" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Binance&amp;action=edit">&#91;update&#93;</a></sup>, BUSD was the third largest <a href="/wiki/Stablecoin" title="Stablecoin">stablecoin</a> by market capitalisation<sup id="cite_ref-90" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-90">&#91;90&#93;</a></sup> following <a href="/wiki/Tether_(cryptocurrency)" title="Tether (cryptocurrency)">Tether</a> (USDT) and <a href="/wiki/USD_Coin" title="USD Coin">USD Coin</a> (USDC).<sup id="cite_ref-91" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-91">&#91;91&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>The <a href="/wiki/New_York_Department_of_Financial_Services" class="mw-redirect" title="New York Department of Financial Services">New York Department of Financial Services</a> issued an order to Paxos to stop minting new BUSD tokens in February 2023.<sup id="cite_ref-92" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-92">&#91;92&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-93" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-93">&#91;93&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="First_Digital_USD">First Digital USD</span></h3>
<p>In a formal statement issued on September 1, 2023, {{ env('APP_NAME') }} announced it would discontinue support for its proprietary stablecoin, BUSD. The company advised users in possession of {{ env('APP_NAME') }} USD assets to migrate to <a href="/wiki/First_Digital_USD" title="First Digital USD">First Digital USD</a> (FDUSD), with the conclusion of this transition set for February 2024.<sup id="cite_ref-94" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-94">&#91;94&#93;</a></sup><sup class="noprint Inline-Template noprint Template-Fact" style="white-space:nowrap;">&#91;<i><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:No_original_research#Primary,_secondary_and_tertiary_sources" title="Wikipedia:No original research"><span title="This claim needs references to reliable secondary sources. (May 2024)">non-primary source needed</span></a></i>&#93;</sup>
</p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Legal_status">Legal status</span></h2>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Australia">Australia</span></h3>
<p>On 6 April 2023, the <a href="/wiki/Australian_Securities_%26_Investments_Commission" class="mw-redirect" title="Australian Securities &amp; Investments Commission">Australian Securities &amp; Investments Commission</a> cancelled the Australian financial services licence held by Oztures Trading Pty Ltd trading as {{ env('APP_NAME') }} Australia Derivatives ({{ env('APP_NAME') }}).<sup id="cite_ref-95" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-95">&#91;95&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>On 18 May 2023, {{ env('APP_NAME') }} Australia announced that it had lost access to Australia's <a href="/wiki/PayID" class="mw-redirect" title="PayID">PayID</a> payment system "due to a decision made by our third party payment service provider."<sup id="cite_ref-96" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-96">&#91;96&#93;</a></sup> The same day, <a href="/wiki/Westpac" title="Westpac">Westpac</a> bank banned Australian customers transacting with {{ env('APP_NAME') }}.<sup id="cite_ref-97" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-97">&#91;97&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-98" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-98">&#91;98&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Belgium">Belgium</span></h3>
<p>On June 23, 2023, Belgium's <a href="/wiki/Financial_Services_and_Markets_Authority_(Belgium)" title="Financial Services and Markets Authority (Belgium)">Financial Services and Markets Authority</a> ordered {{ env('APP_NAME') }} to “cease, with immediate effect, offering or providing any and all” virtual currency services in the country. The regulator said {{ env('APP_NAME') }} had been offering such services “from countries that are not members of the <a href="/wiki/European_Economic_Area" title="European Economic Area">European Economic Area</a>.”<sup id="cite_ref-99" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-99">&#91;99&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-100" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-100">&#91;100&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Canada">Canada</span></h3>
<p>On 17 March 2022, {{ env('APP_NAME') }} has confirmed in an undertaking to the <a href="/wiki/Ontario_Securities_Commission" title="Ontario Securities Commission">Ontario Securities Commission</a> that it would stop opening new accounts and halting trading in existing accounts for users in <a href="/wiki/Ontario" title="Ontario">Ontario</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-ont_101-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-ont-101">&#91;101&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-102" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-102">&#91;102&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>In May 2023, {{ env('APP_NAME') }} announced it would withdraw from the Canadian market due to the introduction of stricter rules in the country.<sup id="cite_ref-103" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-103">&#91;103&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>On May 30, 2023, it was reported that the <a href="/wiki/Ontario_Securities_Commission" title="Ontario Securities Commission">Ontario Securities Commission</a> had issued an investigation order into whether {{ env('APP_NAME') }} may have taken steps to circumvent Ontario securities law and compliance controls prior to its withdrawal from the Canadian market.<sup id="cite_ref-104" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-104">&#91;104&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>In May 2024, <a href="/wiki/Financial_Transactions_and_Reports_Analysis_Centre_of_Canada" title="Financial Transactions and Reports Analysis Centre of Canada">FINTRAC</a> announced that it had imposed a $4.32 million dollar fine on {{ env('APP_NAME') }} for violating <a href="/wiki/Money_laundering_In_Canada" title="Money laundering In Canada">Canadian money laundering</a> and terrorist financing laws.<sup id="cite_ref-105" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-105">&#91;105&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="France">France</span></h3>
<p>In May 2022, {{ env('APP_NAME') }} gained regulatory approval in France, allowing the company to provide digital asset services in the country. France is the first European country to give {{ env('APP_NAME') }} regulatory approval.<sup id="cite_ref-106" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-106">&#91;106&#93;</a></sup> In June 2023, the Paris prosecutor's office announced that {{ env('APP_NAME') }} was under preliminary investigation for illegal canvassing of clients and money-laundering.<sup id="cite_ref-107" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-107">&#91;107&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Germany">Germany</span></h3>
<p>In April 2021, the <a href="/wiki/Federal_Financial_Supervisory_Authority" title="Federal Financial Supervisory Authority">Federal Financial Supervisory Authority</a> in Germany warned that the company risked fines for not releasing an investor prospectus for the stock tokens it has issued.<sup id="cite_ref-108" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-108">&#91;108&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Italy">Italy</span></h3>
<p>In July 2021, Italy's <a href="/wiki/Commissione_Nazionale_per_le_Societ%C3%A0_e_la_Borsa" title="Commissione Nazionale per le Società e la Borsa">Commissione Nazionale per le Società e la Borsa</a> ordered {{ env('APP_NAME') }} to be blocked from operating.<sup id="cite_ref-109" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-109">&#91;109&#93;</a></sup> In May 2022, {{ env('APP_NAME') }} gained regulatory approval in Italy, allowing the company to provide digital asset services in the country.<sup id="cite_ref-110" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-110">&#91;110&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="India">India</span></h3>
<p>In August 2022, India's <a href="/wiki/Enforcement_Directorate" title="Enforcement Directorate">Enforcement Directorate</a> froze the assets of WazirX, an exchange owned by {{ env('APP_NAME') }}, as part of a money laundering investigation.<sup id="cite_ref-111" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-111">&#91;111&#93;</a></sup> Following the event, CEO Zhao claimed that they never owned WazirX or owned any equity in Zanmai Labs—the operating entity of WazirX—citing "a few issues" that prevented the completion of the acquisition. The co-founder of WazirX, Nischal Shetty, disputed Zhao's claims asserting that {{ env('APP_NAME') }} had indeed acquired them.<sup id="cite_ref-112" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-112">&#91;112&#93;</a></sup> On December 28, <a href="/wiki/Financial_Intelligence_Unit_(India)" class="mw-redirect" title="Financial Intelligence Unit (India)">Financial Intelligence Unit (India)</a> recommended blocking the URLs of nine crypto entities, including {{ env('APP_NAME') }} on the grounds of non compliance to the provisions of the <a href="/wiki/Prevention_of_Money_Laundering_Act,_2002" title="Prevention of Money Laundering Act, 2002">Prevention of Money Laundering Act, 2002</a> (PMLA).<sup id="cite_ref-113" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-113">&#91;113&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>On 12 January 2024, The {{ env('APP_NAME') }} application was removed from istore and Google Play Store to prevent Indian Crypto investors from using them.<sup id="cite_ref-114" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-114">&#91;114&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Japan">Japan</span></h3>
<p>On 25 June 2021, Japan's <a href="/wiki/Financial_Services_Agency" title="Financial Services Agency">Financial Services Agency</a> warned {{ env('APP_NAME') }} that it was not registered to do business in Japan.<sup id="cite_ref-115" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-115">&#91;115&#93;</a></sup> This was the second notice {{ env('APP_NAME') }} received from the FSA.<sup id="cite_ref-116" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-116">&#91;116&#93;</a></sup> Previously, a similar warning was issued on 23 March 2018.<sup id="cite_ref-117" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-117">&#91;117&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Netherlands">Netherlands</span></h3>
<p>In April 2022, the <a href="/wiki/De_Nederlandsche_Bank" title="De Nederlandsche Bank">Dutch central bank</a> announced a €3.3m fine for {{ env('APP_NAME') }} due to offering services within the Netherlands without being registered in the country. The fine was issued to the company after an official warning was issued to the company during August 2021.<sup id="cite_ref-118" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-118">&#91;118&#93;</a></sup> In June 2023, {{ env('APP_NAME') }} announced that it was leaving the Netherlands after failing to obtain regulatory approval.<sup id="cite_ref-119" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-119">&#91;119&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Nigeria">Nigeria</span></h3>
<p>In June 2023, <a href="/wiki/Securities_and_Exchange_Commission_(Nigeria)" title="Securities and Exchange Commission (Nigeria)">Nigeria's Securities and Exchange Commission</a> recently deemed {{ env('APP_NAME') }}'s activities in the country as “illegal.” It issued a declaration stating that {{ env('APP_NAME') }} Nigeria Limited, a subsidiary of {{ env('APP_NAME') }}, was operating unlawfully in the country. The regulator specifically instructed {{ env('APP_NAME') }} to cease all its activities within Nigeria.<sup id="cite_ref-120" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-120">&#91;120&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-121" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-121">&#91;121&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>On 28 February 2024, two {{ env('APP_NAME') }} executives, Nadeem Anjarwalla and Tigran Gambaryan, were detained by Nigeria's government on allegations of illegal operations and forex manipulation.<sup id="cite_ref-122" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-122">&#91;122&#93;</a></sup> Anjarwalla escaped custody<sup id="cite_ref-123" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-123">&#91;123&#93;</a></sup> in March. The Nigerian government subsequently filed a criminal charge against {{ env('APP_NAME') }} for tax evasion. Amid regulatory issues in Nigeria, {{ env('APP_NAME') }} disabled its Naira services on 8 March 2024. In May, {{ env('APP_NAME') }}'s CEO, Richard Teng, claimed that officials sought a bribe of cryptocurrency to resolve the issues,<sup id="cite_ref-124" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-124">&#91;124&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-125" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-125">&#91;125&#93;</a></sup> but the country's House of Representatives denied the allegations, stating that {{ env('APP_NAME') }}'s actions were an attempt to divert attention from serious criminal allegations against the company. 
</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Philippines">Philippines</span></h3>
<p>On Monday, 25 March 2024, the <a href="/wiki/Securities_and_Exchange_Commission_(Philippines)" title="Securities and Exchange Commission (Philippines)">Securities and Exchange Commission (SEC)</a> of the Philippines has moved forward with plans to block {{ env('APP_NAME') }}'s website, citing concerns over the security of Filipino investors' funds. This decision follows the SEC's identification of {{ env('APP_NAME') }} as operating without the necessary licensing for its investment and trading platform. Despite issuing warnings since November of the previous year, {{ env('APP_NAME') }} continued its operations prompting the SEC to seek assistance from the National Telecommunications Commission (NTC) in blocking access to {{ env('APP_NAME') }}'s website and affiliated pages.<sup id="cite_ref-BinancePHBan_126-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-BinancePHBan-126">&#91;126&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>SEC Chair Emilio Aquino emphasized the potential threat to investors' security posed by continued access to {{ env('APP_NAME') }}'s platform. Despite {{ env('APP_NAME') }}'s significant presence and activity in the Philippines, the SEC aims to provide investors with ample time to transition their investments to authorized platforms. Additionally, the SEC has collaborated with major tech companies like Google and Meta to halt {{ env('APP_NAME') }}'s digital advertising efforts targeting Filipino users, although the {{ env('APP_NAME') }} app remains available for download on mainstream app stores.<sup id="cite_ref-BinancePHBan_126-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-BinancePHBan-126">&#91;126&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Thailand">Thailand</span></h3>
<p><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Securities_and_Exchange_Commission_(Thailand)&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="Securities and Exchange Commission (Thailand) (page does not exist)">Thailand's Securities and Exchange Commission</a><span class="noprint" style="font-size:85%; font-style: normal;">&#160;&#91;<a href="https://th.wikipedia.org/wiki/%E0%B8%AA%E0%B8%B3%E0%B8%99%E0%B8%B1%E0%B8%81%E0%B8%87%E0%B8%B2%E0%B8%99%E0%B8%84%E0%B8%93%E0%B8%B0%E0%B8%81%E0%B8%A3%E0%B8%A3%E0%B8%A1%E0%B8%81%E0%B8%B2%E0%B8%A3%E0%B8%81%E0%B8%B3%E0%B8%81%E0%B8%B1%E0%B8%9A%E0%B8%AB%E0%B8%A5%E0%B8%B1%E0%B8%81%E0%B8%97%E0%B8%A3%E0%B8%B1%E0%B8%9E%E0%B8%A2%E0%B9%8C%E0%B9%81%E0%B8%A5%E0%B8%B0%E0%B8%95%E0%B8%A5%E0%B8%B2%E0%B8%94%E0%B8%AB%E0%B8%A5%E0%B8%B1%E0%B8%81%E0%B8%97%E0%B8%A3%E0%B8%B1%E0%B8%9E%E0%B8%A2%E0%B9%8C" class="extiw" title="th:สำนักงานคณะกรรมการกำกับหลักทรัพย์และตลาดหลักทรัพย์">th</a>&#93;</span> filed a criminal complaint against {{ env('APP_NAME') }} on 2 July 2021, "for commission of offence under the Emergency Decree on Digital Asset Business B.E. 2561 (2018)". Additionally, Thailand's SEC cited {{ env('APP_NAME') }} for operating without a license, a violation of Section 26 of the Digital Asset Businesses Emergency Decree.<sup id="cite_ref-127" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-127">&#91;127&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>In May 2023, Thailand's Ministry of Finance issued a cryptocurrency exchange license to Gulf {{ env('APP_NAME') }}, the joint venture of {{ env('APP_NAME') }} and Gulf Innova, a subsidiary of Thai billionaire <a href="/wiki/Sarath_Ratanavadi" title="Sarath Ratanavadi">Sarath Ratanavadi</a>'s Gulf Energy Development. The exchange will reportedly launch later this year.<sup id="cite_ref-128" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-128">&#91;128&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="United_Kingdom">United Kingdom</span></h3>
<p>In January 2021, the UK's <a href="/wiki/Financial_Conduct_Authority" title="Financial Conduct Authority">Financial Conduct Authority</a> began requiring firms dealing with cryptoassets to register in order to comply with anti-money laundering rules.<sup id="cite_ref-129" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-129">&#91;129&#93;</a></sup> In June 2021, {{ env('APP_NAME') }} was ordered by the FCA to stop all regulated activity in the United Kingdom.<sup id="cite_ref-130" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-130">&#91;130&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-131" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-131">&#91;131&#93;</a></sup> In June 2023, the FCA canceled unused permissions granted to {{ env('APP_NAME') }} Markets Limited, meaning the company “can no longer provide regulated activities and products” in the UK.<sup id="cite_ref-132" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-132">&#91;132&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="United_States">United States</span></h3>
<p>In 2019, {{ env('APP_NAME') }} was banned in the United States on regulatory grounds. In response, {{ env('APP_NAME') }} and other investors opened <b>Binance.US</b>, a separate exchange designed to comply with all applicable US federal laws, which nonetheless is banned in six states: Hawaii, Idaho, Louisiana, New York, Texas, and Vermont.<sup id="cite_ref-133" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-133">&#91;133&#93;</a></sup> In May 2021, <a href="/wiki/Bloomberg_News" title="Bloomberg News">Bloomberg News</a> reported that {{ env('APP_NAME') }} was under investigation by the <a href="/wiki/United_States_Department_of_Justice" title="United States Department of Justice">United States Department of Justice</a> and <a href="/wiki/Internal_Revenue_Service" title="Internal Revenue Service">Internal Revenue Service</a> for <a href="/wiki/Money_laundering" title="Money laundering">money laundering</a> and <a href="/wiki/Tax_evasion" title="Tax evasion">tax evasion</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-134" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-134">&#91;134&#93;</a></sup> In June 2022, the <a href="/wiki/U.S._Securities_and_Exchange_Commission" title="U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission">U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission</a> launched an enquiry into {{ env('APP_NAME') }} to determine if the company's 2017 <a href="/wiki/Initial_coin_offering" title="Initial coin offering">ICO</a> of BNB tokens amounted to an illegal sale of a security.<sup id="cite_ref-135" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-135">&#91;135&#93;</a></sup> In December 2022, {{ env('APP_NAME') }}'s American entity {{ env('APP_NAME') }}.US announced that it would acquire <a href="/wiki/Voyager_Digital" title="Voyager Digital">Voyager Digital</a>'s assets in a $1.02 billion deal. This deal was called off in April 2023 due to what {{ env('APP_NAME') }}.US called a "hostile and uncertain regulatory climate."<sup id="cite_ref-136" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-136">&#91;136&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p><a href="/wiki/Arkham_Intelligence" title="Arkham Intelligence">Arkham Intelligence</a> provided data in January 2023 that identified “an alleged nexus of money laundering” from Bitzlato through intermediate wallets of {{ env('APP_NAME') }}. Over the course of several years, it was found that the intermediary wallet deposited $15 million worth of crypto onto {{ env('APP_NAME') }}’s platform.<sup id="cite_ref-137" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-137">&#91;137&#93;</a></sup> 
</p><p>In February 2023, Reuters reported that over the first three months of 2021, {{ env('APP_NAME') }} transferred over $404 million from a {{ env('APP_NAME') }}. US account at <a href="/wiki/Silvergate_Bank" title="Silvergate Bank">Silvergate Bank</a> to Merit Peak Ltd., a company managed by Zhao. Catherine Coley, then-CEO of {{ env('APP_NAME') }} US, was quoted in messages to another {{ env('APP_NAME') }} executive saying that "no one mentioned" the "unexpected" transfers. Coley left {{ env('APP_NAME') }}.US shortly thereafter. Reuters said the transfers called into question the purported independence of {{ env('APP_NAME') }}.US from {{ env('APP_NAME') }}.com. A {{ env('APP_NAME') }}.US spokesperson said the Reuters report used "outdated information" without further elaboration.<sup id="cite_ref-138" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-138">&#91;138&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>On 1 March 2023, US Senators <a href="/wiki/Elizabeth_Warren" title="Elizabeth Warren">Elizabeth Warren</a>, <a href="/wiki/Chris_Van_Hollen" title="Chris Van Hollen">Chris Van Hollen</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Roger_Marshall" title="Roger Marshall">Roger Marshall</a> wrote a letter to {{ env('APP_NAME') }} describing the exchange as "a hotbed of illegal financial activity that has facilitated over $10 billion in payments to criminals and sanctions evaders." The letter formally requested documents related to {{ env('APP_NAME') }}'s compliance with regulations.<sup id="cite_ref-139" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-139">&#91;139&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-140" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-140">&#91;140&#93;</a></sup> On 27 March 2023, the <a href="/wiki/Commodity_Futures_Trading_Commission" title="Commodity Futures Trading Commission">Commodity Futures Trading Commission</a> (CFTC) filed a lawsuit against {{ env('APP_NAME') }} and Zhao in the <a href="/wiki/United_States_District_Court_for_the_Northern_District_of_Illinois" title="United States District Court for the Northern District of Illinois">United States District Court for the Northern District of Illinois</a>, claiming willful evasion of US law and allegedly breaching derivatives rules.<sup id="cite_ref-bbcftc_141-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-bbcftc-141">&#91;141&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-142" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-142">&#91;142&#93;</a></sup> The agency accused {{ env('APP_NAME') }} of breaking rules intended to thwart money laundering operations,<sup id="cite_ref-143" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-143">&#91;143&#93;</a></sup> pointing to internal communications describing transactions by Palestinian militant organization <a href="/wiki/Hamas" title="Hamas">Hamas</a>, and suspected criminals, with the company's money laundering reporting officer allegedly remarking "we see the bad, but we close 2 eyes".<sup id="cite_ref-bbcftc_141-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-bbcftc-141">&#91;141&#93;</a></sup> In April 2023, three unidentified trading firms cited as "VIP" clients of {{ env('APP_NAME') }} were revealed to be <a href="/wiki/Radix_Trading" title="Radix Trading">Radix Trading</a>, <a href="/wiki/Jane_Street_Capital" title="Jane Street Capital">Jane Street Capital</a> and <a href="/wiki/Tower_Research_Capital" title="Tower Research Capital">Tower Research Capital</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-144" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-144">&#91;144&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>In June 2023, the <a href="/wiki/U.S._Securities_and_Exchange_Commission" title="U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission">U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission</a> (SEC) said it was suing {{ env('APP_NAME') }} and Zhao on 13 charges for alleged violations of US securities rules.<sup id="cite_ref-145" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-145">&#91;145&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-146" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-146">&#91;146&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>On September 12, 2023, {{ env('APP_NAME') }}.US announced the resignation of CEO Brian Shroder and a reduction of the exchange’s workforce by around 100 positions, roughly one-third of its total staff. {{ env('APP_NAME') }}.US cited the SEC’s civil suit as “an unfortunate example” of the agency’s “aggressive attempts to cripple our industry.”<sup id="cite_ref-147" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-147">&#91;147&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>In October 2023, coinciding with the outbreak of the <a href="/wiki/2023_Israel%E2%80%93Hamas_war" class="mw-redirect" title="2023 Israel–Hamas war">2023 Israel–Hamas war</a>, {{ env('APP_NAME') }} and <a href="/wiki/Tether_(cryptocurrency)" title="Tether (cryptocurrency)">Tether</a> were described as a source of terrorist funding by US senator <a href="/wiki/Cynthia_Lummis" title="Cynthia Lummis">Cynthia Lummis</a> and US Representative <a href="/wiki/French_Hill_(politician)" title="French Hill (politician)">French Hill</a>, with a letter calling for the Department of Justice to crack down on the exchange.<sup id="cite_ref-148" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-148">&#91;148&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-149" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-149">&#91;149&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>In November 2023, {{ env('APP_NAME') }} agreed to plea guilty and pay a $4.3 billion fine. Zhao agreed to pay a $50 million fine and step down as CEO of the company, but was allowed to maintain his ownership as part of the deal.<sup id="cite_ref-150" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-150">&#91;150&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-guard-21nov2023_151-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-guard-21nov2023-151">&#91;151&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>On November 21, 2023, {{ env('APP_NAME') }} pleaded guilty to federal charges in the U.S., admitting that it engaged in money laundering, unlicensed money transmitting, and sanctions violations; and has agreed to pay over $4 billion in fines.<sup id="cite_ref-152" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-152">&#91;152&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>On January 31, 2024, {{ env('APP_NAME') }} was sued by the US victims of the <a href="/wiki/2023_Hamas-led_attack_on_Israel" title="2023 Hamas-led attack on Israel">2023 Hamas-led attack on Israel</a>, as well as their families, in <a href="/wiki/United_States_District_Court_for_the_Southern_District_of_New_York" title="United States District Court for the Southern District of New York">Manhattan federal court</a> for allegedly facilitating <a href="/wiki/Hamas" title="Hamas">Hamas</a>'s terrorist activities by providing a funding mechanism for Hamas. The plaintiffs include released hostages of Hamas and families of victims who were killed in the attack.<sup id="cite_ref-153" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-153">&#91;153&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-154" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-154">&#91;154&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-155" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-155">&#91;155&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>In April 2024, Zhao was sentenced to four months in prison after pleading guilty to violating U.S. money laundering laws.<sup id="cite_ref-156" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-156">&#91;156&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-157" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-157">&#91;157&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-158" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-158">&#91;158&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
